    <item>
      <title>25week20 - Jabberwocky correlated</title>
      <link>http://192.168.178.34:1313/posts/25/250518_25week20---jabberwocky-correlated/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 18 May 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://192.168.178.34:1313/posts/25/250518_25week20---jabberwocky-correlated/</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.openculture.com/2025/05/the-world-record-for-the-shortest-math-article.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The World Record for the Shortest Math Article: 2 Words&#8599;</a> And John Conway was involved, of course he was.</p>
<p>




<center style="color:var(--default_dim_fg);"> ─ </center>




Correlations are overused these days, primarily to reduce complex social problems into basic and extreme narratives. These are later transformed into political benefits for buffoons. Anyhow, this site is mostly for the lolz, and it does create some funny <a href="https://www.tylervigen.com/spurious-correlations" target="_blank" rel="noopener">spurious correlations&#8599;</a></p>
<p>




<center style="color:var(--default_dim_fg);"> ─ </center>




<a href="https://pointerpointer.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Place your cursor anywhere and wait&#8599;</a></p>
<p>




<center style="color:var(--default_dim_fg);"> ─ </center>




<a href="http://Neal.fun" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Neal.fun&#8599;</a> is probably one of the most famous people in creating these little games easy to share and equally fun and educational. In his internet artifacts, you can find an enormous amount of internet history facts, like <a href="https://neal.fun/internet-artifacts/earliest-lol/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the earliest lol&#8599;</a></p>
<p>




<center style="color:var(--default_dim_fg);"> ─ </center>




The first stanza to what would become <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabberwocky" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Jabberwocky&#8599;</a>: Stanza of Anglo-Saxon Poetry</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Twas bryllyg, and þe slythy toves<br>
Did gyre and gymble in þe wabe:<br>
All mimsy were þe borogoves;<br>
And þe mome raths outgrabe.</p>
</blockquote>





<center style="color:var(--default_dim_fg);"> ─ </center>




<p>Listening: <strong>The Tree of the Left Hand by Arianne Churchman &amp; Benedict Drew</strong>



